teristic forenames:  Jewish Meyer, Emanuel, Este, Hyman, Isador, Isadore, Isidor, Yetta.","English (Middlesex, of Norman origin): nickname or occupational name from Old French <i>c(h)aunteor</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>c(h)aunter</i> ‘singer, chorister, one who leads the singing’, also (in Old French) ‘poet, minstrel’. The earliest examples of this surname are from Latin <i>cantor</i> (the ancestor of the Old French word) and refer to precentors in cathedrals or monasteries, while the modern surname, of Old French origin, will have originally denoted a secular singing role. Compare   Canter  .","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Kantor  ."]},{"name":"Cantrall","meanings":["English: variant of   Cantrell  ."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margery Cantrell was born in 1370, in Bache, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with John Chauntrell. She died in 1433, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1370–1433":"1370–1433","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1400–1439":"1400–1439","1415–1455":"1415–1455","1415":"1415","1400":"1400","about 1415":"umbes 1415","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","1370":"1370","1439":"1439","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Bache, Cheshire, England":"Bache, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1370–1433":"1370–1433","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1400–1439":"1400–1439","1415–1455":"1415–1455","1415":"1415","1400":"1400","about 1415":"noin 1415","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","1370":"1370","1439":"1439","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Bache, Ches